Iu like manner the Rule of St. Benedict: ‘⁶ Nullatenus liceat monacho nec a parentibus suis, nec a quoquam hominum, nec sibi invicem literas, aut Eulogia, vel quaelibet munuscula accipere aut dare, sine praecepto Abbatis sui.”—cap. 54 (Nov. Bibl. Vet. Patr. tom. i. p. 701, Par. 1639). The pre— sent passage shows that in the Irish Church, in St. Columba's time, it was the practice to participate reverentially of the Eulogiae at the commencement of the afternoon meal, and in the refectory. The later manuscripts, to ac- commodate the practice to more modern usage, substitute oratorio for refectorio, but in violence to the context, which adds, ¹⁴ festinanter pergit hac cum voce ad ecclesiam, Non est nobis nunc temporis prandere.
